1
00:00:01,140 --> 00:00:06,459
The Ichimoku Cloud is a versatile indicator
that defines support and resistance, identifies

2
00:00:06,459 --> 00:00:10,530
trend direction, shows momentum and provides
trading signals.

3
00:00:10,530 --> 00:00:16,129
Even though the Ichimoku Cloud may seem complicated
when viewed on the price chart, it's actually

4
00:00:16,129 --> 00:00:21,240
a rather straightforward indicator; the concepts
are easy to understand and the signals are

5
00:00:21,240 --> 00:00:22,609
well-defined.

6
00:00:22,609 --> 00:00:28,009
Ichimoku takes multiple averages, plots them
on the chart and uses these figures to compute

7
00:00:28,009 --> 00:00:33,070
a "cloud" which attempts to forecast where
the price may find support or resistance in

8
00:00:33,070 --> 00:00:34,190
the future.

9
00:00:34,190 --> 00:00:37,750
The Ichimoku Cloud consists of five lines.

10
00:00:37,750 --> 00:00:44,760
Conversion Line, Base Line, Lagging Span,
Leading Span A and Leading Span B.

11
00:00:44,760 --> 00:00:49,870
First component: Conversion Line, also known
as Tenkan-Sen

12
00:00:49,870 --> 00:00:53,539
The Conversion Line shows the short-term price
momentum.

13
00:00:53,539 --> 00:00:59,219
On its own, it shows the mid-point price over
the last 9 periods, which is the default value

14
00:00:59,219 --> 00:01:01,280
for this indicator.

15
00:01:01,280 --> 00:01:04,989
Conversion Line signals an area of minor support
or resistance.

16
00:01:04,989 --> 00:01:11,250
• If the market price is above the conversion
line, this indicates a short-term upward momentum,

17
00:01:11,250 --> 00:01:13,640
and you would want to concentrate on buying
signals

18
00:01:13,640 --> 00:01:19,520
• If the price is below conversion line,
this shows a short-term downward momentum,

19
00:01:19,520 --> 00:01:24,880
and you would want to search for selling signals
• An increasing conversion line, meaning

20
00:01:24,880 --> 00:01:30,159
an upward slope, indicates an upward trend
• A decreasing conversion line, meaning

21
00:01:30,159 --> 00:01:36,950
a downward slope, indicates a downward trend
Due to the very short-term nature of the indicator,

22
00:01:36,950 --> 00:01:41,549
it is not typically used on its own but rather
used in conjunction with the other elements

23
00:01:41,549 --> 00:01:44,600
of the Ichimoku Cloud.

24
00:01:44,600 --> 00:01:51,130
Second component is the base line, also known
as the Kijun-sen or the confirmation line.

25
00:01:51,130 --> 00:01:56,200
The base line serves as a signal for support
and resistance levels on medium term.

26
00:01:56,200 --> 00:02:01,930
The base Line is the mid-point of the high
and low price over the last 26 periods.

27
00:02:01,930 --> 00:02:07,340
On its own, the base line can also be used
for analyzing price momentum.

28
00:02:07,340 --> 00:02:12,470
• When the price is above the base line,
it means the price is above 26-period mid-point

29
00:02:12,470 --> 00:02:14,560
and therefore has an upward bias.

30
00:02:14,560 --> 00:02:19,810
• If the price is below the base Line, it
is below the mid-point price, and therefore

31
00:02:19,810 --> 00:02:22,170
has a downward bias.

32
00:02:22,170 --> 00:02:25,390
• An increasing slope of the base line indicates
an upward trend

33
00:02:25,390 --> 00:02:30,840
• A decreasing slope of the base line indicates
a downward trend

34
00:02:30,840 --> 00:02:36,230
Unless there is a very strong trend, the base
line will often appear near the price.

35
00:02:36,230 --> 00:02:41,580
When the base Line is often intersecting or
near the price, it is not as useful for helping

36
00:02:41,580 --> 00:02:44,069
to evaluate the trend direction.

37
00:02:44,069 --> 00:02:50,390
Third component: lagging span, also referred
to as Chikou Span

38
00:02:50,390 --> 00:02:56,650
The lagging span is created by plotting closing
prices 26 periods behind the latest closing

39
00:02:56,650 --> 00:02:58,760
price of an instrument.

40
00:02:58,760 --> 00:03:03,940
This lagging line is designed to allow traders
to visualize the relationship between current

41
00:03:03,940 --> 00:03:07,990
and prior trends, as well as to spot potential
trend reversals.

42
00:03:07,990 --> 00:03:13,310
One of the key ways to use to the indicator
is to view its relationship to the current

43
00:03:13,310 --> 00:03:14,510
price.

44
00:03:14,510 --> 00:03:19,250
• When the price is below the lagging span,
this is usually an indication there is strength

45
00:03:19,250 --> 00:03:22,359
in the price and it is moving higher.

46
00:03:22,359 --> 00:03:26,970
• When the price appears above the lagging
line, this is often an indication there is

47
00:03:26,970 --> 00:03:29,290
weakness in the price.

48
00:03:29,290 --> 00:03:33,990
If it appears that the lagging line is about
to cross above the prior price line, it would

49
00:03:33,990 --> 00:03:39,500
be a bullish confirmation sign, while a span
that is crossing underneath would be a bearish

50
00:03:39,500 --> 00:03:41,799
confirmation sign.

51
00:03:41,799 --> 00:03:46,480
Trading signals based on the Chikou span are
strongest when it doesn’t touch or cross

52
00:03:46,480 --> 00:03:49,480
over any the prior candles.

53
00:03:49,480 --> 00:03:54,709
Any interaction with the past price line is
an indication of a choppy or sideways market.

54
00:03:54,709 --> 00:04:00,980
If a lagging line is descending quickly into
a past price line, it could be a sign of exhaustion

55
00:04:00,980 --> 00:04:02,819
for the asset.

56
00:04:02,819 --> 00:04:09,790
Forth component: Kumo cloud, which is formed
from 2 lines (leading span a and leading span

57
00:04:09,790 --> 00:04:13,370
b)
The Kumo Cloud provides support/resistance

58
00:04:13,370 --> 00:04:17,030
levels that can be projected into the future.

59
00:04:17,030 --> 00:04:22,250
This sets the Ichimoku Cloud apart from many
other technical indicators that only provide

60
00:04:22,250 --> 00:04:26,090
support and resistance levels for the current
date and time.

61
00:04:26,090 --> 00:04:31,890
The uptrend is strengthened when the Leading
Span A (green cloud line) is rising and above

62
00:04:31,890 --> 00:04:34,740
the Leading Span B (red cloud line).

63
00:04:34,740 --> 00:04:38,040
This situation produces a green cloud.

64
00:04:38,040 --> 00:04:44,150
Conversely, a downtrend is reinforced when
the Leading Span A (green cloud line) is falling

65
00:04:44,150 --> 00:04:46,400
and below the Leading Span B (red cloud line).

66
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:49,600
This situation produces a red cloud.

67
00:04:49,600 --> 00:04:55,480
Because the cloud is shifted forward 26 periods,
it also provides a glimpse of future support

68
00:04:55,480 --> 00:04:56,970
or resistance.

69
00:04:56,970 --> 00:05:02,160
If it is thick, then the support/resistance
is strong (depending on the position of price

70
00:05:02,160 --> 00:05:03,770
in relation to the cloud).

71
00:05:03,770 --> 00:05:09,600
By contrast, if it is thin, then the S/R levels
are considered weak.

72
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:14,780
Generally, if the price is above the Kumo,
then there is an uptrend in place and/or more

73
00:05:14,780 --> 00:05:16,900
buying opportunities.

74
00:05:16,900 --> 00:05:22,270
If the price is below the Kumo, then it is
under resistance and it is better to be looking

75
00:05:22,270 --> 00:05:25,800
for shorts instead of longs.

76
00:05:25,800 --> 00:05:31,070
The longer price action stays above or below
the Kumo, the stronger the trend and the more

77
00:05:31,070 --> 00:05:34,320
support/resistance the Kumo offers.

78
00:05:34,320 --> 00:05:40,750
The Kumo can be very effective for long term
traders as well as for trend/momentum traders.

79
00:05:40,750 --> 00:05:45,620
This is because price will stay on one side
of the Kumo cloud during a trend.

80
00:05:45,620 --> 00:05:51,020
The farther the price action is from it, the
stronger the trend and more volatile it is.

81
00:05:51,020 --> 00:05:56,030
Generally, you should avoid trading inside
the Kumo cloud, as it signals a period of

82
00:05:56,030 --> 00:05:58,440
indecision.

83
00:05:58,440 --> 00:06:03,890
As a type of moving average system, Ichimoku
signals are generated by crossovers of the

84
00:06:03,890 --> 00:06:07,960
key lines, namely conversion line and base
line.

85
00:06:07,960 --> 00:06:13,690
When the Tenkan/conversion line crosses over
the Kijun/base line, it generates a buying

86
00:06:13,690 --> 00:06:14,690
signal.

87
00:06:14,690 --> 00:06:21,650
A signal to sell appears when the Tenkan/conversion
line crosses below the Kijun/ base line.

88
00:06:21,650 --> 00:06:26,400
But in Ichimoku theory, the signals are not
created equal, and this is where the cloud

89
00:06:26,400 --> 00:06:27,960
comes into play.

90
00:06:27,960 --> 00:06:33,630
If the two lines cross to the downside while
current prices are above the cloud, only a

91
00:06:33,630 --> 00:06:36,130
weak sell signal is generated.

92
00:06:36,130 --> 00:06:41,690
The strongest sell signal appears when the
downside crossover occurs while prices are

93
00:06:41,690 --> 00:06:47,900
below the cloud, essentially signaling that
fresh weakness is now evident within an overall

94
00:06:47,900 --> 00:06:49,330
downtrend.

95
00:06:49,330 --> 00:06:55,630
The same guidelines apply to upside crossovers
generating buy signals and the location of

96
00:06:55,630 --> 00:07:01,440
current prices to the cloud, with the strongest
buy signal coming from an upside crossover

97
00:07:01,440 --> 00:07:04,470
while prices are above the cloud.

98
00:07:04,470 --> 00:07:09,810
Here are several examples of conversion line
- base line crossovers, with Kumo cloud as

99
00:07:09,810 --> 00:07:27,060
filter.

100
00:07:27,060 --> 00:07:31,310
The chikou/lagging span provides yet another
way to evaluate the strength of the crossover

101
00:07:31,310 --> 00:07:35,930
signals given by the tenkan/conversion line
and kijun/base lines.

102
00:07:35,930 --> 00:07:41,150
Remember that the chikou/lagging span is simply
today’s closing price projected 26 days

103
00:07:41,150 --> 00:07:47,740
into the past, providing a clear look at today’s
market level relative to earlier prices.

104
00:07:47,740 --> 00:07:52,910
If a sell signal is generated on a downside
crossover and the chikou/lagging span is below

105
00:07:52,910 --> 00:07:57,170
the price candles, the signal is considered
stronger.

106
00:07:57,170 --> 00:08:02,500
If a crossover to the upside occurs and the
chikou/lagging span is above prices, then

107
00:08:02,500 --> 00:08:06,510
a higher probability is attached to the buy
signal.

108
00:08:06,510 --> 00:08:11,640
Again, the idea is that a crossover in the
direction of the overall trend is considered

109
00:08:11,640 --> 00:08:16,390
more powerful than one that is against the
trend.

110
00:08:16,390 --> 00:08:21,340
The crossover between span lines forming the
Kumo cloud is another trading strategy used

111
00:08:21,340 --> 00:08:26,400
by traders, in a similar fashion to a moving
average crossover.

112
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:32,720
However, remember that the lines of the cloud
are projected forward by 26 periods.

113
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:38,270
• when leading span A of the Kumo cloud
crosses above span b, and prices are positioned

114
00:08:38,270 --> 00:08:41,441
above the Kumo cloud, we have a strong buy
signal

115
00:08:41,441 --> 00:08:47,440
• when leading span A of the Kumo cloud
crosses below span b, and prices are positioned

116
00:08:47,440 --> 00:08:50,459
below the Kumo cloud, we have a strong sell
signal

117
00:08:50,459 --> 00:08:56,000
• when leading span A of the Kumo cloud
crosses above span b, but prices are positioned

118
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:02,110
below the Kumo cloud, we have a weak buy signal
• when leading span A of the Kumo cloud

119
00:09:02,110 --> 00:09:07,120
crosses below span b, but prices are positioned
above the Kumo cloud, we have a weak sell

120
00:09:07,120 --> 00:09:09,840
signal

121
00:09:09,840 --> 00:09:13,030
Another trading technique involves the Kumo
cloud breakout.

122
00:09:13,030 --> 00:09:17,130
This signal occurs when the price cuts through
the Kumo cloud.

123
00:09:17,130 --> 00:09:21,270
• when the price enters the Kumo cloud and
breaks its upper line, we have a bullish signal

124
00:09:21,270 --> 00:09:27,300
• when the price enters the Kumo and breaks
its lower line, we have a bearish signal

125
00:09:27,300 --> 00:09:31,860
If the price is clearly above or below it,
then when price action breaks the kumo, it

126
00:09:31,860 --> 00:09:34,340
can often signal a reversal.

127
00:09:34,340 --> 00:09:38,450
There are several factors which increase the
chances of a reversal, such as:

128
00:09:38,450 --> 00:09:43,030
· The thickness of the Kumo when broken
· The amount of time price action has been

129
00:09:43,030 --> 00:09:47,860
on one side of it
· How far price action has moved before touching/breaking

130
00:09:47,860 --> 00:09:51,870
the Kumo
· and also the time frame

131
00:09:51,870 --> 00:09:57,920
Ichimoku relies on only three different time
periods in its calculations: nine, 26 and

132
00:09:57,920 --> 00:09:59,030
52.

133
00:09:59,030 --> 00:10:03,610
Japanese financial markets used to be open
for trading on Saturdays, meaning that the

134
00:10:03,610 --> 00:10:06,030
trading week was six days long.

135
00:10:06,030 --> 00:10:11,800
As a result, the number nine represents a
week and a half of trading; 26 equals the

136
00:10:11,800 --> 00:10:17,820
number of trading days in a typical month
(30 minus four Sundays); and 52 equals two

137
00:10:17,820 --> 00:10:19,590
months of trading days.

138
00:10:19,590 --> 00:10:25,470
Japanese markets now trade only five days
per week, so some practitioners of Ichimoku

139
00:10:25,470 --> 00:10:30,590
suggest revising the parameters to seven,
22 and 44.

140
00:10:30,590 --> 00:10:37,020
In my experience, however, the traditional
default settings of nine, 26 and 52 have performed

141
00:10:37,020 --> 00:10:39,250
the best.

142
00:10:39,250 --> 00:10:41,560
Ichimoku does have its limitations.

143
00:10:41,560 --> 00:10:46,640
Let’s face it, the indicator can make a
chart look busy with all the lines.

144
00:10:46,640 --> 00:10:51,380
To remedy this, depending on your trading
needs, certain lines can be hidden.

145
00:10:51,380 --> 00:10:57,170
For example, all the lines can be hidden except
for the Leading Span A and B which create

146
00:10:57,170 --> 00:10:58,430
the cloud.

147
00:10:58,430 --> 00:11:03,410
You need to focus on which lines provide the
most information for you, and then consider

148
00:11:03,410 --> 00:11:07,640
hiding the rest if all the lines are distracting.

149
00:11:07,640 --> 00:11:12,470
Another limitation of the Ichimoku Cloud is
that it is based on historical data.

150
00:11:12,470 --> 00:11:17,020
While two of these data points are plotted
in the future, there is nothing in the formula

151
00:11:17,020 --> 00:11:18,650
that is predictive.

152
00:11:18,650 --> 00:11:22,030
Averages are simply being plotted in the future.

153
00:11:22,030 --> 00:11:27,160
The cloud can also become irrelevant for long
periods of time, as the price remains way

154
00:11:27,160 --> 00:11:29,080
above or below it.

155
00:11:29,080 --> 00:11:34,620
At times like these, the conversion line,
base line, and their crossovers become more

156
00:11:34,620 --> 00:11:39,340
important, as they generally stick closer
to the price.

157
00:11:39,340 --> 00:11:43,800
